namespace JSX Elements Table

This document shows a huge table of JSX HTML Elements, it is generated using ./jsx/data.json. The table is automated and generated on demand, with live data taken from the frameworks repos, mdn, and browsers via puppeteer. Very few of the data is hardcoded (such some of the obsolete attributes/properties/tags that no longer exists in MDN).

  • Tag Names: The tagNames come from a mashup between frameworks and TypeScript TagNamesMaps data.
  • Interfaces: The interface names comes from document.createElementNS(ns, tagName).constructor.name, which is more accurate than typescript.
  • Properties: Chrome/Firefox attributes come from brute-forcing the element setters till an attribute is added. The name of the attribute is taken as key. When something is marked as prop it means Chrome or Firefox has a setter for it.
  • üóëÔ∏è indicates that the tag or attribute is deprecated (live from mdn + hardcoded)
  • üõë indicates that the key resembles a prop but such a prop does not exist. Setting node.propName = value will not produce the expected result. Frameworks are strongly discouraged from inventing non-existent properties (e.g., keys with custom casing, except for event handlers like onClick). This can cause confusion. For example, autoFocus does not exist; the correct name is autofocus.
  • üîó indicates the prop it's inherited (from the element prototype chain)
  • ‚ò¢ indicates the key it's experimental (live from mdn)
  • ‚ö† indicates the key it's non-standard (live from mdn)
  • ‚Åâ indicates something weird is going on with key (to be investigated)
  • ‚ùó‚ùó‚ùó indicates the attribute wasn't autodiscovered and need corroboration, or that it just doesnt exists.
  • SVG is not shown because it needs some more work

This is an attempt to unify the effort required to update this information.
